author: Dan Ferguson
title: VIDEO: Newcomers celebrate first Canadian winter by skating on frozen pond in B.C.
text:
Siblings Avery, two, and Blake, four, came in from Surrey with dad Mark and mom Kerrianne for their first experience of a skate on outdoor ice at Brydon Lagoon in Langley City on Sunday, Jan 14.
All were well bundled up against the below-freezing weather.
‚ÄúWe just moved here from California,‚Äù Kerrianne explained.
‚ÄúOur friends live here in Langley, and they told us that the lagoon was frozen over, and the girls have never seen it [outdoor ice].‚Äù
Mark said the cold temperatures was a big change from the San Francisco Bay area, where they were living.
‚Äú[It‚Äôs] just an experience for the girls, their first time on the ice,‚Äù he said.
‚ÄúWe just moved up here and figured we‚Äôd we‚Äôd commit to it [the weather].‚Äù
Langley City residents Shaquil and Audrey, the Canadian friends who made the call to the newcomers from California, brought daughter Zaiya, 16 months, who was beaming as dad towed her on a sled.
‚ÄúI grew up around here,‚Äù explained Shaquil, who recently moved back to his home town after working in the U.S.
‚ÄúSeeing this lagoon freeze over, it‚Äôs just been really nice. It‚Äôs very nostalgic.‚Äù
He was excited to share the experience with the friends from California.
‚ÄúThey‚Äôre now going to be residents for the foreseeable future, so they‚Äôve got to get into the Canadian way,‚Äù he smiled.
READ ALSO:
A frozen Brydon Lagoon becomes a giant ice rink
After several days of chilly weather, Environment Canada was forecasting a return to warmer conditions later in the week, rising to a high of plus-five and a low of plus-one by Thursday, Jan. 18, with periods of rain.
READ ALSO:
Coffee certificates and cab rides: how Langley‚Äôs homeless are being helped during cold snap
As a matter of policy, the City of Langley is against skating on Brydon, and likes to remind residents that any pond in the City, including Brydon Lagoon, is not a ‚Äúsanctioned skating rink.‚Äù
‚ÄúThe City has not tested the thickness of the ice and cannot confirm it is safe,‚Äù a 2021 warning posted to social media advised.

author: Canadian Press
title: Alberta Premier Smith says legislation on school pronouns coming after September
text:
EDMONTON ‚Äî Alberta Premier Danielle Smith says her government will introduce legislation on pronouns in schools after classes begin in September.
Smith says the new policy requiring parents to be notified when kids 15 and under want to change their names or pronouns in schools will be proposed in the fall legislature session that begins in late October.
Her comments come about three weeks before most Kindergarten to Grade 12 schools open their classrooms.
Smith says she intends to bring legislation forward for a suite of policies she first announced in January.
Those include restricting trans youth access to gender-affirming health care, banning trans participation in female sports, and requiring parental consent on sex education and changes to pronouns and names in schools.
LGBTQ+ advocacy groups have said they plan to challenge the new provincial policies in court, following similar legal action in Saskatchewan.
This report by The Canadian Press was first published Aug. 15, 2024.
The Canadian Press

title: F1 Protests Surge: Renault Staff Oppose Engine Program Cancellation
text:
F1 Protests Surge: Renault Staff Oppose Engine Program Cancellation
Renault F1 staff are intensifying protests against the company's decision to abandon its in-house engine program for the Alpine team. Following a peaceful demonstration at Monza, workers also staged a strike at the engine factory in France. Despite the turmoil, Renault CEO Luca de Meo claims the decision to switch to Mercedes engines for 2026 isn‚Äôt final, but employee dissatisfaction is growing. With backing from the CGT labor union, additional protests have taken place, including one at Renault's headquarters and another at Le Mans. Employees seek assurance that all factors are considered before the final decision is made.By the Numbers
- 100 Renault staff protested at global headquarters in Boulogne-Billancourt.
- Approximately 40 engine staff demonstrated at the Le Mans circuit.
While management insists the engine program's fate is undecided, staff's escalating protests reflect deep-rooted frustration. The union's support indicates a broader sentiment among workers who feel marginalized in the decision-making process.State of Play
- Protests are gaining momentum as employees organize demonstrations across key locations.
- Support from labor unions highlights the seriousness of staff discontent regarding management decisions.
As protests continue, Renault may face increased pressure from both employees and labor unions. The outcome of these actions could influence the company's final decision on the future of their F1 engine program.Bottom Line
Renault F1‚Äôs engagement in protests underscores a critical juncture for the company; a disconnect exists between management and staff that could severely impact team morale and future performance if not addressed.
